segments.text: You and General Dean stayed with the plane.
Actually, it's funny to talk about these things.
And it's interesting, I think.
It's fascinating.
This is common, ordinary things that happen in a relation between nations.
That's the reason to me that they're so meaningful looking back now.
And in this particular case, I got to talk and live and eat and get drunk with almost.
I was still a fine ambassador.
I couldn't get drunk, but I had a lot of vodka that evening with the commander of a Red Air Force fighter squadron.
No telling how many guys, Germans, this guy had to his credit.
And through the interpreter sitting right between us, the interpreter for the ambassador, this Navy lieutenant.
And by the way, he had time for his life, too.
He didn't have flies, so he could drink.
But he would interpret.
And we talked like an Air Force man to another Air Force man.
There was no problem whatsoever.
So they took you into town.
Yeah, took us into town and put us up in a dormitory that was fortunately still standing.
Part of it had been blown to pieces.
Every place was almost just cleared to the ground, razed to the ground, demolished.
How about the people?
Very few people I saw.
I don't know where they were.
I guess they were living in the ground.
Even they had the P-39s around the field on alert.
They had them backed off into sort of a dugout ramp, like you would have put a tank.
Sure.
They'd roll them down to at least get them with the wall levees around them, you know.
A gun emplacement-like thing is what they had them parked in.
And they still expected German attacks from them.
Sure.
They worried about us being there.
There might be a German attack on us.
And rightfully concerned about the Ambassador to the United States.
But I had conversations with the squad.
They gave us a deal.
So that evening, all of you went, everybody on the plane went to dinner.
Yeah.
General Dean ended up finally took him over to where the Ambassador was staying.
I don't know where it was.
But my crew and me and the Ambassador's interpreter were somehow or another, he stayed with us.
And through him, and actually I was talking with this Red Air Force pilot, fighter pilot.
And typical, typical American fighter pilot.
Typical.
You mean he was like an American?
Except for his language and his uniform, I would have thought I was talking to another American fighter pilot.
No kidding.
And even, you know, after two drinks, oh, he says, when we take care of the Germans, he said, don't worry, don't worry, we're going to take care of the Japanese.
No problem.
Don't worry.
When we get to the Germans, and they kaput soon, and then that kaput Japan.
What about, did you swap some stories about the flying tigers?
Oh, yeah.
Had he heard of the flying tigers?
Yes, since you brought it up, I think he had heard about this.
He had no respect for Japanese whatsoever.
He thought it would be simple.
No respect.
It must have been easy over there, something like that, you know.
But he and I just got along great.
And I gave him my Zippo cigarette lighter and I think he gave me a little tiny ivory bone, I guess, type cigarette lighter.
It didn't even work.
We changed that as gifts to one another.
Was he a colonel?
No.
I don't remember what his rank was.
He couldn't have been over a major rank.
But he was a squadron commander.
And very young, very young, but a lot of combat experience, no doubt.
And cocky, typical, typical fighter pilot.
A tiger, if you will.
And the next morning, of course then we went to bed, the next morning we got up, and for breakfast we had raw fish and vodka.
Raw fish and vodka.
And you had to chew on it a little to be courteous because the Russians, you know that old
fighter pilot sat right next to me, just gobbling it up, and toasting me in vodka.
You know, I had to, I felt free to tell him, look, I've got to fly the airplane, but I'll sip it with you.
And most cordial, most cordial.
No problem whatsoever, you know.
Then you think back to the problem we're having in Russia now, compared to our discussion there with a Red Air Force fighter pilot.
But that's the story.
Isn't that incredible?
Let me, the airplane picks the problem.
But did you, because of this conversation with this fighter pilot, did you have different, did you come to different thoughts about the average Russian?
No, as a matter of fact, it's been firm.
I can't talk about the man on the street, on the lower strata of people, when you sit down and talk, communicate.
Many times,
in subsequent meetings with the Red Air Force who was supporting us at the shuttle bases, you know, staying there overnight on many meetings with them and talking to them.
It was this same type of camaraderie, no problem whatsoever.
Just very close feelings.
To me, I felt closer to them than I would if I'd talked to a ramp pilot or air pilot.
No kidding?
Oh, yeah.
Just like a typical... Matter of fact, I liked them.
And utmost confidence.
I was sure that guy could take on any German fighter pilot and whip him any day.
That's how I felt about it.
So you had a high regard then for the military man in the Russian Air Force.
Like I say, it would be a terrible, terrible conflict.
But, you know, those boys are gone now.
They're like me.
They're 16, 17, retired.
Many of them are dead.
Russia hasn't been fighting a war like we have, so I don't know how combat experience they have, how much they have in their current forces.
I see evidence of it in pictures, but how much of it is propaganda?
Did you leave the next morning then?
Yeah, took off the next morning and went on down to Cairo.
And the airplane was?
No problem.
Had a very good crew.
I forget what problem, was it an oil valve or something?
Where'd you get the part?
Didn't need a part.
Cleaning or something?
Or a leak.
One came loose, and I'm getting one of those.
Now, tell me about some other field visits that you made.
Well, most of the other visits were down at the shuttle bases.
I go down there frequently.
Piraeacan, Poltava, and- Poltava?
Poltava.
In Romania?
Poltava and the Ukraine area.
Okay, in the Ukraine.
Yeah.
The three of them.
Two of them were bomber recovery bases and one was a fighter recovery base and it was just wide open field area where steel planking for runways were laid down by Red Army women.
A force of Red Army women.
And many of the support forces that they moved into the bases to take care of, you can tell they were
typical Red Army uniform.
Always that huge ankle-length overcoat.
Just to see it every place.
Every one of them.
The girl, the man, the kid, all of them wore that same.
Air Force guy, the Army guy, the Navy guy, they always wore that long overcoat.
The, what were the fields?
The field for the
We had a permanent force of Americans at three bases and it took months.
That was a problem.
We were trying to get adequate force to run the bases in order to take care of the reception of the aircraft and where to park them and take care of them.
And I think we were holding out for, oh, initially around 2,000, 2,500, something like that.
We ended up with 1,200.
Russians always said, no, we'll take care of it.
We'll take care of it.
We'll take care of that.
So you had about 1,200 men at each one of these.
1,200 Americans.
And each one of them had to have visas.
That's another thing that held us up.
Each one of them had to have visas.
Generally stating.

The difficulty we had in laying on these bases and laying on for military operations, we continually came face to face with the Red Army, with the communist bureaucracy of keeping foreigners out of the nation.
Sure.
Keep it at an absolute minimum.
If the ones that are permitted, they must be documented and have visas and research and so forth and so on.
And it took time, just interminable delays.
Everything we did took delays.
Very, very frustrating.
But being determined, we did it.
And I don't know how many Russians they had to support and supply and feed us, but they had enough.
And they did the job.
The bases were hit.
And we lost a lot of B-17s over there one night.
And this, they, part of the agreement was, they would provide the air defense.
They would not permit us to have any air defense forces there at all.
No fighters.
No fighters at all.
Only bombers.
As a matter of fact, our fighters, the bombers, would not be permitted to take off in an air defense role.
This was all understood before we even laid on any of the missions.
But before we get to the attack, to go back to the support was adequate.
But the time it took to do things is what was so frustrating.
Tents were arranged and put up for the crew.
The crew slept in tents.
And they'd just stay long enough to rearm, refuel, and then take off on another mission and go back, really, about an overnight stay, weather familiar.
Generally, that's the way the missions were run.
And they had, you know, open mess with mess kits and all.
They had to bring the mess kits.
And they went so far at first to demand that the crew members on a flight must have visas before they made a shuttle mission.
Well, eventually, up to ambassadorial level, and maybe even stalling above Molotov, I don't know, but we got that eliminated.
That was just, you know, impossible.
Plus, it made...
jeopardize the mission by giving away some of the secrecy.
Well, at times you almost came to the conclusion that they were purposely putting these obstacles in your path to discourage us from doing it.
Looking back now, I don't think they really, matter of fact, I know they didn't want to do this because it exposed their country and their situation more to foreigners, a la the Berlin Wall.
They just wanted us out.
They didn't want
foreigners in.
So tell me about the conditions of these three bases.
They were livable.
The steel plank, of course, we had experience operating on them.
We knew that there was no problem operating on those.
On the steel planks?
Yeah.
Landing and take-offs.
The parking, as long as it wasn't in
In bad weather, if it rained, we'd have to cancel the mission because these airplanes, particularly loaded B-17s, couldn't taxi that mud, black mud of the Ukraine.
Crimea, not Crimea, but the Ukraine area.
No concrete, of course.
But we had enough maintenance people locally just for turnaround, and 1,200 people we had, including That's 1,200 at each base.
Totally.
They had about 400 men at each base.
Right, and a certain amount of that was staff to maintain relations with General Perminoff, who was a Russian general in charge.
He supported the three bases.
They had a little organization, and we had a little organization.
I think they came out of the 8th Air Force.
The food was adequate.
Mostly flown in by the bombers?
Mostly the food was flown in by the bombers?
No, no.
Matter of fact, we flew supplies in around through Tehran and up from Tehran in transport aircraft.
One of the biggest problems was the belly tanks that we had to ferry in on each mission, or at least have ready at the base.
I think it was about 30 or 40 of them, see, recovered in one base.
And they'd dropped their tanks, see, on the flight across.
They'd used up their fuel, and the only way to get back was to have more fuel tanks, belly tanks.
So we had to ferry those in.
And here they'd stop the transport at Tehran and say they had to wait to get visas for the crew.
Well, that, of course, that actually caused several missions to be scrubbed.
Many times, the protocol demands of the bureaucracy of Moscow caused us to struggle out of bombing missions.
As time went on, we worked out some of these problems where things got a little more routine, and it worked a little bit more smoothly.
Towards the end, it was working fairly well.
But just with this containing persistence, did we ever get anything done.
But eventually, it got done.
So the food was adequate, and the men slumped in tents.
And they'd come in off a mission over Germany, land in the Ukraine, stay there overnight, refuel, and rearm, and hit Germany on the way back to France.
Yeah, on the way back, primarily Germany.
And then, of course, 15th Air Force Midley began to make missions up.
fly across and hit maybe Romania or Germany or some place, then recover and fly back.
It was effective, and of course it made for closer coordination, supposedly, between Russia and us in the eventual pizza movement against Germany.
But looking back now, I'm not too sure how
effective it was because there was one colonel assigned to our mission in Moscow who was to coordinate targeting for the Red Air Force.
And this was to always know exactly where the front lines of the Russians were so when we planned a target we didn't want to overrun.
And they were advancing very rapidly and taking the big cities back.
So we had to maintain close liaison with them.
But this colonel who had that job initially met with a Red Air Force colonel in the Kremlin and met him and discussed what they were supposed to do.
That's the only time he ever saw him.
He remained over there for six months, never had another meeting, and got to the point where he said, boy, he almost became an alcoholic.
They just sent him back.
That was the amount of coordination between the forces for Pinsonville.
So you never did bomb then?
There was never an occasion.
So you only bombed from the American side and you never bombed for the Red Army advancing?
See, that's one of the things we wanted to do.
We wanted to coordinate with the advances and make bomb targets really in effect, if you will, tactical support in advance of the oncoming Red Army.
They never did work out that way.
The Russians didn't want us to do it because they figured we'd destroy places and they wanted to take them intact and they didn't want
want to destroy it.
They didn't want to do it.
So basically, they didn't want to work with us on it.
They just worked with us on the surface.
Follow General Book, General Dean Book, The Strange Alliance.
Right.
Now, what about, now there's been the issue of American air flyers and crews that went down right on or around behind the Russian lines.
And after the war, the

We were wondering if they had held any of those people, and I've read some of the dispatches from Harriman back to Roosevelt in which he says that the Russians weren't very forthcoming about getting our pilots back to the embassy and then we could fly them out again.
Do you remember anything like that?
I remember the Pacific Cape you're talking about.
The Pacific Cape you're talking about,
to a B-29 crew in a Japanese war, an attack against Japan where a B-29 had to recover in Russia, north of Vladivostok area, because of maintenance problems, or maybe damage.
But some way or another, and this was sort of the early periods of this type of coordination relation with Russia.
They held the crew, and some way or another, they just
wouldn't cooperate with the ambassador in transferring them to Moscow, where if the ambassador didn't want to talk to them, they'd get them on home.
For some reason or another, they just wouldn't do it, and it took the ambassador a long time, and personally, I think personally,
Probably, Roosevelt eventually probably sent out a personal water stallion.
I have an idea he must have.
But eventually it broke loose, and all of a sudden it just broke loose, and no problem whatsoever.
It was exactly the reverse.
They couldn't do enough for us to cooperate, to get the crew back and all.
Just outstanding, you know.
But that's the only occasion I remember at first.
After that, I guess after the decision was made, passed down to the chain, and there was no fear of superiors
Maybe a Russian was doing something wrong, and the stage was set, and orders were given, and that thing worked all right after that.
Now, the few Russians, the few Americans that were shot down behind a Russian mine were in the European theater of operation.
Normally, there was a few occasions of that happening, and there was no particular problem getting those politics back.
They were helpful.
Yeah.
Cooperative helpful.
I say cooperative and helpful.
In the way you and I look at it, you might say, well, reluctantly they did it, or with delaying tactics they did it.
Just never, never been able to understand why this, except that maybe superstition and fear of doing something wrong from above.
Discipline is a, discipline in Russia is a, in my opinion, a terrible thing.
A mistake made in Russia, to me, must be a terrible thing.
In time of war, I'm sure many of them were shot.
On this flight I was telling you about, where I was a navigator back from out of the cockpit, it was after the Tehran conference.
The ambassador wanted to get back to Moscow very fast.
The weather was terrible, horrible.
Snow stormed all the way up.
And he couldn't fly above them?
Yeah.

Well, to fly above them, that's what I tried to do, but there was no nav agent in Moscow at that time, except for me trying to monitor a commercial radio station, maybe with my radio compass, and then there's still no letdown procedure.
And whether there it goes clear, it goes around, zero, zero.
But at any rate, I took off and said, we can try it.
Well, I wanted to.
I wanted to impress Molotov.
Who sent out that message?
impressed Molotov and says, do you think we can do it?
And I said, well, we can try, I think we can.
I remember General Dean was worried.
Why did he want to impress Molotov?
Well, see, one of our objectives was to build up the Air Transport Command routes.
They showed that weather was no problem.
We could get through, you know, with an airplane.
Molotov went back by rail.
And I took off and started back.
And by the way, we had the British Ambassador aboard, too, in that flight.
And I got Norris.
Did you really?
Yeah.
take him back.
It was after the Tehran conference, going back to Moscow.
What was his name, Lord?
He was a tall Scottish man.
Well, Clark Carr was later, but this was not Clark Carr, this was a man before him.
And I met him, by the way, and loved him.
Love Clark Carr?
Oh, that's true.
But anyway, we took off and I got a little north of Donningrath.
one of my checkpoints.
And it was beginning to get over the overcast and I didn't want to do it.
So I turned around, went back down to where the overcast ran out, let down and then came back and was going to fly under it all the way to Moscow.
And it kept getting lower and lower and lower and finally I was, you know, over 500 feet above the ground.
Fortunately, it was snowing, and as a result of continual snowing, not real dense snow, I could see forward visibility of maybe a couple of miles.
But as a result of the snowing, the precipitation didn't fog up or anything, so I could see well enough.
It was that way all the way up to Moscow.
But I got lost.
The navigator had no idea where I was, and I looked over at him, Russian navigator, and boy, his beads were swept around me as far as he was scared to death.
And finally I looked over at my copilot and I said, get walked up there, my navigator.
So I told him.
First I had to get the interpreter up and tell him to get this Russian navigator back.
Boy, he didn't want to go, but I said, back?
First time I ever talked in a
command directly to him, back.
And we got back and got my navigator out there and we took him back.
He says, we'll just find a double railroad.
There's a double railroad here someplace.
We find that.
We know that leads to Moscow.
And I found it.
And got right down on top of that railroad, flying about 1,500 feet above it.
No kidding?
With my head stuck out in a bubble on the side of my airplane, flying it manually all the way to Moscow.
And as we came into Moscow Of course, you knew the terrain.
There weren't any mountains.
Oh, no, it's flat.
Wasn't anything.
No mountains or noit was sort of prairie land all the way down.
And not even any rolling hills, just flat.
And you know, as long as it stayed above that railroad, there couldn't be anything higher than the railroad poles, telephone poles.
And finally hit
the city of Moscow and flew right square over the top of the, I buzzed the Kremlin.
I guess it's the only time it's ever been buzzed.
I couldn't have been over 50 feet above it.
And spied the airport and came in and landed.
And I was, I admit, I was worried.
Here I had the ambassador on board, daughter of General Dean, a British ambassador.
And I must admit, I was real worried.
I had visions of going down, you know,
The responsibility was terrible.
What a relief when I landed there.
First guy that got off was this British, well of course he got off as the ambassador, but he may have gotten in his car and I understand he stayed in bed about a week.
He was scared.
No.
He just got sick.
And the ambassador of course he felt equally as I.
I remember sending a message back to the ambassador telling him, we may have to land at Raman Skoy.
That was a big air base just south of Moscow.
And his, which is typical of him, he's back to the interpreter.
Tell me exactly why you think we will have to land at Raman Skoy.
He didn't pray.
He said, tell me exactly why.
And he told me, well, I'm not sure that I'll be able to fly over the city at low altitude and find Central Airport.
But I will try to get it in Central Airport, where, you know, we're supposed to land, normally land.
So he didn't question me anymore.
But he was equally glad when we landed, I could tell.
As a matter of fact, he came up and personally complimented me and said, you know, something like, I appreciate this.
And I said, I'll tell Mr. Molotov.
The next day, he had a meeting with Mr. Molotov.
Mr. Molotov had heard.
about me ordering this navigator in the back of the airplane.
He told the ambassador all about this.
He had heard that.
Now, that's how it got to him.
And expressed concern that we would take such a chance.
And the ambassador told me, I just, he said, well, I just told him, well, it's typical flights of humor.
We knew we'd make it.
And of course, the ambassador, when he was telling me this, he was kind of grinning about it, too.
He knew it was, but he, he,
He had made a point, you know, with the ambassador.
And he was quite proud of it.
And he thought I was great, even greater than before.
But incidentally, I never saw that navigator again.
No kidding.
They replaced him on the airplane.
End of that story.
Well, that's fascinating.
Did you know Sir Clark, not Clark, Sir Frank Roberts, who was the assistant to Clark Kerr?
in the British Embassy.
He was Kennan's counterpart in the British Embassy.
I'm sure I must have met him, but I don't know him, but I don't remember his name.
Okay.
Were there any other field visits, or have we covered all of those?
Yeah, I think we have.
That's all I've got to take.
I almost got a chance to take a trip along the Transylvania Railroad to Vladivostok, but instead of me they sent an army colonel.
I think it took him ten days to make that trip.
Now let's talk about the conferences.
that you went to, the wartime conferences.
You went to the Tehran conference and the Cairo conference.
Yes.
When I say I went to the conference, I flew the ambassador down.
I didn't actually participate at that level.
No, I know.
But I flew him down, the Tehran conference.
You can imagine the time it took in arrangements that would take to make arrangements like that, and the secrecy of it.
I didn't even know at that time
I'd say until about 24 hours before takeoff of what was going on.
I just figured I was taking the ambassador on a trip to Iran.
And I never did feel free to query the ambassador about anything about why I was going on this trip.
So I didn't know why.
That's how secret it was.
I'm sure if Moscow proper only
In our group, I guess, Harriman and General Dean knew about the planning.
Probably counting until?
Until 24, I'm sure.
And of course, took him down with General Dean.
General Dean attended with him.
I remember the ambassador, it may have been General Dean who told me this, but I remember this comment.
It sort of compares the three big leaders to you.
Churchill, Darlene, and Roosevelt.
At the opening of the conference, I believe it was Ambassador Herman telling General Dean about this, or then General Dean telling me, or maybe it was Ambassador Herman who told me about this.
He said, Mr. Roosevelt stood up and made a very good opening speech, you know, very impressive as usual and all.
It took five or six minutes.
Then Mr. Churchill got up, and as usual, kicking English around.
He did terrific.
He made a wonderful speech and all, and sat down.
And Staline got up and said to his interpreter, gentlemen, let's get to work, and sat down.
Staline, I met him and shook hands with him.
Tell me about that.
When we presented our credentials initially, you know, when I first arrived in Moscow, when the ambassador presented his credentials, I went with him.
I actually shook hands with Stalin, a little sharp guy, very impressive.
And obviously to me, you know, here I am meeting Stalin.
Tell me about that.
Well, I was impressed with the man.
He was sharp and another human being.
When I look back now, but in the Kremlin, me, Charlie Baum, taking hands with Mr. Starling, I'll never forget it.
And of course, I was impressed.
I was impressed with the surroundings, just the occasion, and just overall.
That's the closest that I ever got to him.
I did see him a couple of times at the Bolshoi Theater on a special performance when Churchill visited.
Incidentally, he hated Churchill's guts and vice versa.
And Harriman and Roosevelt knew it.
Roosevelt had to be sort of a temporal or the arbitrating type of a guy between them.
They despised each other.
Tell me about the Kremlin and Stalin's office.
I was never in Stalin's office.
We were in the reception room where Stalin came into.
It's a typical government bureaucratic building, if you will.
If I remember correctly, the walls, sort of a fortress wall around the entire Kremlin.
The Kremlin is a group of buildings.
Oh, yeah.
Well, you've seen it.
The inside of it is the grounds of manicure in the summertime.
Of course, everything covers snow in the wintertime.
But if I remember correctly, the buildings were cream plastered.
And not bleak like right outside the walls of the Kremlin, like the city was.
Bleak and dreary and unmaintained.
Inside of it was immaculate.
The inside of the buildings were, comparatively speaking, to our big office buildings and government buildings, very bare.
Pictures on a wall, maybe of Lenin and Stalin.
very, the furniture was just the plainest stuff in the world, even in the main conference room.
Always the green velvet cover for the conference table.
Felt, felt covered, green felt, like a pool table.
That's the typical Russian conference table, with bottles of water, purified water, and
vodka and goblets on the table, Russian cigarettes about, arranged for conferences, neatly, neat and clean inside.
No flies in there, like in Winningfield.
Not primitive in nature there.
In other words, the best of Russia, but yet plain.
No RNA.
Austere is the word.
Austere.
Marble floors, that type of thing.
And, of course, guards and sentries every place.
And when you arrived at the Kremlin, how long did Stalin keep you and Mr. Harriman waiting?
Was Dean with you?
Yes.
You three?
Well, there may have been others, but I remember specifically Mr. Harriman, General Dean,
And since I was the ambassador's aide, I was along.
Now, also, the supply general may have been along, the Lindley supply general.
I forget his name.
Again, it would be in that book, The Stranger Lines.
But he was there.
And I think the reason Mr. Herman's approach, and we actually talked about this at times, it was very evident.
He took all of us along.
Normally, let's say, you know, maybe strictly diplomatically speaking, maybe just he personally, without even an interpreter, should have gone.
But here, you know, I think he was trying to break the wall down between Russia and us from a standpoint of communication and try to get things on an informal basis and
Look, in effect, look, I've got a lot of people here, and I want them to talk.
They've got to talk to your people, and let's talk.
This is always his objective.
And for some reason or another, it didn't take.
He generally got the audience of Molotov any time he asked for it.
And many times, by the way, it's strange,
I'd hear General Dean talk about this, and it always turned out to be even some of the minor conferences between some of the other liaison intelligence people and communications people.
They'd have the conference at maybe 2 o'clock in the morning.
Yeah, I know that.
Stone and Molotov were night people.
They were night people.
Night people?
Oh, yeah.
Matter of fact, the hierarchy.
at night people.
And I dare say this may still be true.
Definitely during the war it was.
And when you went, let's get back to when you presented your credentials.
When you went, you gentlemen went to the Kremlin.
You went to the reception room.
How long did you wait before Stalin came out?
And then can you describe the situation and give me your impressions?
How do we call this waiting too long?
We did wait.
Then he came in the opposite end of the room and made me walk across with an interpreter right next to him, an ambassador, a hairman.
How was he dressed?
I think he was dressed in tunic, military type uniform, army type uniform.
The white one?
No, no.
The greenish gray and the slacks and the tunic buttons all the way at the top.
He rode the Soviet Union, you know, that gold medal hanging from a, I mean the gold star hanging from a little red rivet.
One of those, a mustache.
So he didn't have, he didn't have- I had epaulettes on, but I don't even remember what was on the top of the epaulettes.
Yeah, he had epaulettes on.
I don't remember the insignia on the top.
Well, you know, a lot of the time he was referred to as Marshall Stalin.
Oh, yeah, I know.
OK, so he walked in, and you all stood up?
He walked in, made you walk across to shake hands with the ambassador.
And obviously, I forget exactly what he said, but the interpreter then would tell Mr.
Ambassador and airmen in English, you know, delighted to have you, and all of that type of stuff.
And then right down the line, immediately, you know, going right down to me.
I don't even say anything.
He shook hands with me, and in effect, I don't even
He may have looked at me, but I don't even remember him looking me straight in the eye.
I looked him straight in the eye.
